## Step 1: Apply the distributive property to multiply the two terms
$\left( \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right) = \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right)$
## Step 2: Distribute the terms
$\left( \frac{1}{2} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right) = \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) - \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) - \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{3} \right)$
## Step 3: Simplify each term
$\left( \frac{1}{2} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) - \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) - \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{3} \right) = \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{6} - \frac{1}{9}$
## Step 4: 
$\frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{6} - \frac{1}{9} = \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{9}$
## Step 5: Find a common denominator for the fractions
$\frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{9} = \frac{9}{36} - \frac{4}{36}$
## Step 6: Subtract the numerators
$\frac{9}{36} - \frac{4}{36} = \frac{5}{36}$

$\frac{5}{36}$
